# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: metal-compute
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] In computer graphics, a **shader** is a programmable operation which is applied to data as it moves through the rendering pipeline.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Shaders act on data such as vertices and primitives, generate or morph geometries and fragments, and calculate the colors in a rendered image.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Shaders can execute a wide variety of operations.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] In modern real-time computer graphics, shaders are run on graphics processing units (GPUs) - dedicated hardware which provide parallel execution of programs.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Because image rendering is an embarrassingly parallel problem (having an Amdahl's index of one), shaders benefit greatly from parallel computing, such as SIMD hardware.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The drive for faster rendering has produced highly parallel processors, like GPUs, which are now used for general-purpose computing.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Shaders used for general purposes are commonly called *compute shaders*.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The term "shader" was first introduced to the public by Pixar with version 3.0 of their RenderMan Interface Specification, originally published in May 1988.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] As graphics processing units evolved, major graphics software libraries such as OpenGL and Direct3D began to support shaders.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The first shader-capable GPUs only supported pixel shading, but vertex shaders were quickly introduced once developers realized the power of shaders.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The first video card with a programmable pixel shader was the Nvidia GeForce 3 (NV20), released in 2001.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Geometry shaders were introduced with Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Graphics hardware evolved toward a unified shader model, making all shaders equal.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The traditional use of shaders is to operate on data in the graphics pipeline to control the rendering of an image.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Graphics shaders are classified according to their position in the pipeline, the data being manipulated, and the graphics API being used.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Vertex shaders are run once for each 3D vertex given to the graphics processor.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The purpose is to transform each vertex's 3D position in virtual space to the 2D coordinate at which it appears on the screen (as well as a depth value for the Z-buffer).
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Vertex shaders can manipulate properties such as position, color and texture coordinates, but cannot create new vertices.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The output of the vertex shader goes to the next stage in the pipeline, which is either a geometry shader if present, or the rasterizer.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Vertex shaders can enable powerful control over the details of position, movement, lighting, and color in any scene involving 3D models.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Geometry shaders were introduced in Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2; formerly available in OpenGL 2.0+ with the use of extensions.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] This type of shader can generate new graphics primitives, such as points, lines, and triangles, from those primitives that were sent to the beginning of the graphics pipeline.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Geometry shader programs are executed after vertex shaders.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] They take as input a whole primitive, possibly with adjacency information.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] For example, when operating on triangles, the three vertices are the geometry shader's input.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The shader can then emit zero or more primitives, which are rasterized and their fragments ultimately passed to a pixel shader.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Typical uses of a geometry shader include point sprite generation, geometry tessellation, shadow volume extrusion, and single pass rendering to a cube map.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] A typical real-world example of the benefits of geometry shaders would be automatic mesh complexity modification.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] A series of line strips representing control points for a curve are passed to the geometry shader and depending on the complexity required the shader can automatically generate extra lines each of which provides a better approximation of a curve.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] model rendered using fragment shaders with different outputs: solid white, applied texture, physically based shading.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Fragment shaders, also known as **pixel shaders**, compute color and other attributes of each "fragment": a unit of rendering work affecting at most a single output pixel.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The simplest kinds of pixel shaders output one screen pixel as a color value; more complex shaders with multiple inputs/outputs are also possible.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Pixel shaders range from simply always outputting the same color, to applying a lighting value, to doing bump mapping, shadows, specular highlights, translucency and other phenomena.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] They can alter the depth of the fragment (for Z-buffering), or output more than one color if multiple render targets are active.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] In 3D graphics, a pixel shader alone cannot produce some kinds of complex effects because it operates only on a single fragment, without knowledge of a scene's geometry (i.e. vertex data).
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] However, pixel shaders do have knowledge of the screen coordinate being drawn, and can sample the screen and nearby pixels if the contents of the entire screen are passed as a texture to the shader.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] This technique can enable a wide variety of two-dimensional postprocessing effects such as blur, or edge detection/enhancement for cartoon/cel shaders.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Pixel shaders may also be applied in *intermediate* stages to any two-dimensional images—sprites or textures—in the pipeline, whereas vertex shaders always require a 3D scene.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] For instance, a pixel shader is the only kind of shader that can act as a postprocessor or filter for a video stream after it has been rasterized.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] OpenGL 4.0 and Direct3D 11 introduced a new shader class called a tessellation shader.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The function can be related to a variety of variables, most notably the distance from the viewing camera to allow active level-of-detail scaling.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] This allows objects close to the camera to have fine detail, while further away ones can have more coarse meshes, yet seem comparable in quality.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] It also can drastically reduce required mesh bandwidth by allowing meshes to be refined once inside the shader units instead of down-sampling very complex ones from memory.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Some algorithms can up-sample any arbitrary mesh, while others allow for "hinting" in meshes to dictate the most characteristic vertices and edges.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Circa 2017, the AMD Vega microarchitecture added support for a new shader stage—primitive shaders—somewhat akin to compute shaders with access to the data necessary to process geometry.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Nvidia introduced mesh and task shaders with its Turing microarchitecture in 2018 which are also modelled after compute shaders.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Nvidia Turing is the world's first GPU microarchitecture that supports mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate API, several months before Ampere RTX 30 series was released.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] In 2020, AMD and Nvidia released RDNA 2 and Ampere microarchitectures which both support mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] These mesh shaders allow the GPU to handle more complex algorithms, offloading more work from the CPU to the GPU, and in algorithm intense rendering, increasing the frame rate of or number of triangles in a scene by an order of magnitude.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Intel announced that Intel Arc Alchemist GPUs shipping in Q1 2022 will support mesh shaders.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Ray tracing shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectX Raytracing, by Khronos Group via Vulkan, GLSL, and SPIR-V, by Apple via Metal.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "ray tracing cores".
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Compute kernels are routines compiled for high throughput accelerators (such as graphics processing units (GPUs), digital signal processors (DSPs), or field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs)), separate from but used by a main program (typically running on a central processing unit).
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] They may be specified by a separate programming language such as "OpenCL C", as "compute shaders" written in a shading language, or embedded directly in application code written in a high level language.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Compute kernels roughly correspond to inner loops when implementing algorithms in traditional languages (except there is no implied sequential operation), or to code passed to internal iterators.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Microsoft support this as DirectCompute.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] This single program, multiple data programming paradigm maps well to vector processors: there is an assumption that each invocation of a kernel within a batch is independent, allowing for data parallel execution.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] However, atomic operations may sometimes be used for synchronization between elements (for interdependent work), in some scenarios.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Individual invocations are given indices (in 1 or more dimensions) from which arbitrary addressing of buffer data may be performed (including scatter gather operations), so long as the non-overlapping assumption is respected.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The Vulkan API provides the intermediate SPIR-V representation to describe *both* graphical shaders, and compute kernels in a language independent and machine independent manner.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The intention is to facilitate language evolution and provide a more natural ability to leverage GPU compute capabilities, in line with hardware developments such as Unified Memory Architecture and Heterogeneous System Architecture.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] This allows closer cooperation between a CPU and GPU.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Much work has been done in the field of Kernel generation through LLMs as a means of optimizing code.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] KernelBench, created by the Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford, provides a framework to evaluate the ability of LLMs to generate efficient GPU kernels.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Cognition has created Kevin 32-B to create efficient CUDA kernels which is currently the highest performing model on KernelBench.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Tensor shaders are accelerator programs that deal with matrix operations on large arrays, a type of operation commonly used in neural network-based AI.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Tensor shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectML, by Khronos Group via OpenVX, by Apple via Core ML, by Google via TensorFlow, by Linux Foundation via ONNX.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "tensor cores".
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Several programming languages exist specifically for writing shaders, and which is used can depend on the target environment.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The shading language for OpenGL is GLSL, and Direct3D uses HLSL.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The Metal framework, used by Apple devices, has its own shading language called Metal Shading Language.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Increasingly in modern graphics APIs, shaders are compiled into SPIR-V, an intermediate language, before they are distributed to the end user.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] This standard allows more flexible choice of shading language, regardless of target platform.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] First supported by Vulkan and OpenGL, SPIR-V is also being adopted by Direct3D.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] The graph is then compiled into a shader.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] In web development contexts, visual and component-based shader tools have also emerged.
[src:metal-compute/compute-kernel] Platforms such as shaders.com provide component-driven composition of shaders for integration into frontend frameworks including Vue, React, and Svelte, while tools such as Shadertoy and FragCoord.xyz focus on lower-level shader authoring and debugging.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Essentially, a GPGPU pipeline is a kind of parallel processing between one or more GPUs and CPUs, with special accelerated instructions for processing image or other graphic forms of data.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While GPUs operate at lower frequencies, they typically have many times the number of processing elements.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Thus, GPUs can process far more pictures and other graphical data per second than a traditional CPU.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Migrating data into parallel form and then using the GPU to process it can (theoretically) create a large speedup.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines were developed at the beginning of the 21st century for graphics processing (e.g. for better shaders).
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] From the history of supercomputing it is well-known that scientific computing drives the largest concentrations of Computing power in history, listed in the TOP500: the majority today utilize GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The best-known GPGPUs are Nvidia Tesla that are used for Nvidia DGX, alongside AMD Instinct and Intel Gaudi.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In principle, any arbitrary Boolean function, including addition, multiplication, and other mathematical functions, can be built up from a functionally complete set of logic operators.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In 1987, Conway's Game of Life became one of the first examples of general-purpose computing using an early stream processor called a blitter to invoke a special sequence of logical operations on bit vectors.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] General-purpose computing on GPUs became more practical and popular after about 2001, with the advent of both programmable shaders and floating point support on graphics processors.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Notably, problems involving matrices and/or vectors – especially two-, three-, or four-dimensional vectors – were easy to translate to a GPU, which acts with native speed and support on those types.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A significant milestone for GPGPU was the year 2003 when two research groups independently discovered GPU-based approaches for the solution of general linear algebra problems on GPUs that ran faster than on CPUs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These early efforts to use GPUs as general-purpose processors required reformulating computational problems in terms of graphics primitives, as supported by the two major APIs for graphics processors, OpenGL and Direct3D.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This cumbersome translation was obviated by the advent of general-purpose programming languages and APIs such as Sh/RapidMind, Brook and Accelerator.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These were followed by Nvidia's CUDA, which allowed programmers to ignore the underlying graphical concepts in favor of more common high-performance computing concepts.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Newer, hardware-vendor-independent offerings include Microsoft's DirectCompute and Apple/Khronos Group's OpenCL.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This means that modern GPGPU pipelines can leverage the speed of a GPU without requiring full and explicit conversion of the data to a graphical form.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mark Harris, the founder of GPGPU.org, claims he coined the term *GPGPU*.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Any language that allows the code running on the CPU to poll a GPU shader for return values, can create a GPGPU framework.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programming standards for parallel computing include OpenCL (vendor-independent), OpenACC, OpenMP and OpenHMPP.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As of 2016, OpenCL is the dominant open general-purpose GPU computing language, and is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL provides a cross-platform GPGPU platform that additionally supports data parallel compute on CPUs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is actively supported on Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM platforms.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The Khronos Group has also standardised and implemented SYCL, a higher-level programming model for OpenCL as a single-source domain specific embedded language based on pure C++11.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The dominant proprietary framework is Nvidia CUDA.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia launched CUDA in 2006, a software development kit (SDK) and application programming interface (API) that allows using the programming language C to code algorithms for execution on GeForce 8 series and later GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ROCm, launched in 2016, is AMD's open-source response to CUDA.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is, as of 2022, on par with CUDA with regards to features, and still lacking in consumer support.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenVIDIA was developed at University of Toronto between 2003–2005, in collaboration with Nvidia.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Altimesh Hybridizer created by Altimesh compiles Common Intermediate Language to CUDA binaries.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It supports generics and virtual functions.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Debugging and profiling is integrated with Visual Studio and Nsight.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is available as a Visual Studio extension on Visual Studio Marketplace.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced the DirectCompute GPU computing API, released with the Direct3D 11 API.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] MATLAB supports GPGPU acceleration using the *Parallel Computing Toolbox* and *MATLAB Distributed Computing Server*, and third-party packages like Jacket.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU processing is also used to simulate Newtonian physics by physics engines, and commercial implementations include Havok Physics, FX and PhysX, both of which are typically used for computer and video games.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] C++ Accelerated Massive Parallelism (C++ AMP) is a library that accelerates execution of C++ code by exploiting the data-parallel hardware on GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to a trend of increasing power of mobile GPUs, general-purpose programming became available also on the mobile devices running major mobile operating systems.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Google Android 4.2 enabled running RenderScript code on the mobile device GPU.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] RenderScript has since been deprecated in favour of first OpenGL compute shaders and later Vulkan Compute.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is available on many Android devices, but is not officially supported by Android.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Apple introduced the proprietary Metal API for iOS applications, able to execute arbitrary code through Apple's GPU compute shaders.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Originally, data was simply passed one-way from a central processing unit (CPU) to a graphics processing unit (GPU), then to a display device.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As time progressed, however, it became valuable for GPUs to store at first simple, then complex structures of data to be passed back to the CPU that analyzed an image, or a set of scientific-data represented as a 2D or 3D format that a video card can understand.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Transferring the portion of the data set to be actively analyzed to that GPU memory in the form of textures or other easily readable GPU forms results in speed increase.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The distinguishing feature of a GPGPU design is the ability to transfer information bidirectionally back from the GPU to the CPU; generally the data throughput in both directions is ideally high, resulting in a multiplier effect on the speed of a specific high-use algorithm.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines may improve efficiency on especially large data sets and/or data containing 2D or 3D imagery.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is used in complex graphics pipelines as well as scientific computing; more so in fields with large data sets like genome mapping, or where two- or three-dimensional analysis is useful – especially at present biomolecule analysis, protein study, and other complex organic chemistry.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An example of such applications is NVIDIA software suite for genome analysis.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such pipelines can also vastly improve efficiency in image processing and computer vision, among other fields; as well as parallel processing generally.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some very heavily optimized pipelines have yielded speed increases of several hundred times the original CPU-based pipeline on one high-use task.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example would be a GPU program that collects data about average lighting values as it renders some view from either a camera or a computer graphics program back to the main program on the CPU, so that the CPU can then make adjustments to the overall screen view.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A more advanced example might use edge detection to return both numerical information and a processed image representing outlines to a computer vision program controlling, say, a mobile robot.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU as a software concept is a type of algorithm, not a piece of equipment.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Specialized equipment designs may, however, even further enhance the efficiency of GPGPU pipelines, which traditionally perform relatively few algorithms on very large amounts of data.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Massively parallelized, gigantic-data-level tasks thus may be parallelized even further via specialized setups such as rack computing (many similar, highly tailored machines built into a *rack*), which adds a third layer – many computing units each using many CPUs to correspond to many GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some Bitcoin "miners" used such setups for high-quantity processing.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Insights into the largest such systems in the world has been maintained at the TOP500 supercomputer list.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Historically, CPUs have used hardware-managed caches, but the earlier GPUs only provided software-managed local memories.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, as GPUs are being increasingly used for general-purpose applications, state-of-the-art GPUs are being designed with hardware-managed multi-level caches which have helped the GPUs to move towards mainstream computing.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, GeForce 200 series GT200 architecture GPUs did not feature an L2 cache, the Fermi GPU has 768 KiB last-level cache, the Kepler GPU has 1.5 MiB last-level cache, the Maxwell GPU has 2 MiB last-level cache, and the Pascal GPU has 4 MiB last-level cache.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs have very large register files, which allow them to reduce context-switching latency.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Register file size is also increasing over different GPU generations, e.g., the total register file size on Maxwell (GM200), Pascal and Volta GPUs are 6 MiB, 14 MiB and 20 MiB, respectively.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] By comparison, the size of a register file on CPUs is small, typically tens or hundreds of kilobytes.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In essence: almost all GPU workloads are inherently massively-parallel LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE in nature, such as tiled rendering.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Even storing one temporary vector for further recall (LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE-COMPUTE-LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE) is so expensive due to the memory wall problem that it is to be avoided at all costs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result is that register file size *has* to increase.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In standard CPUs it is possible to introduce caches (a D-cache) to solve this problem, however these are relativrly so large that they are impractical to introduce in GPUs which would need one per processing element.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ILLIAC IV innovatively solved the problem around 1967 by introducing a local memory per processing element (a PEM): a strategy copied by the Aspex ASP.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Much like how CPUs may elect to implement wider vector instructions in smaller pieces (e.g.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] AMD Bulldozer supported the 256-bit AVX instructions by splitting them into two 128-bit operations) to save power and/or chip area, GPU designers also vary the amount of execution units to fit their expected workloads.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On a GPGPU, each of the following resources can vary freely in ratio from the others: FP64 (FMA), FP32 (FMA), FP16 (FMA), Int32 Add, Int32 Mul, RCP/RSQRT.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] (An example can be seen in Nvidia's documentation about the execution resources found in each SM of different generation (compute capacity) of GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is therefore insufficient to simply qualify a GPU's computational capabilities in terms of FLOPS: FLOPS values should be separately presented for matrix vs non-matrix modes and (T)OPS figures should also be presented for integer operations.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The high performance of GPUs comes at the cost of high power consumption, which under full load is in fact as much power as the rest of the PC system combined.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The maximum power consumption of the Pascal series GPU (Tesla P100) was specified to be 250W.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In terms of raw computing power (FLOPS, TOPS, etc.), GPUs tend to have more performance-per-watt than a typical CPU.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, it takes a well-written program and a fitting workload to extract most of this power, as most of the time (and power) would otherwise be wasted on local and host memory access.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Before CUDA was published in 2007, GPGPU was "classical" and involved repurposing graphics primitives.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] More examples are available in part 4 of *GPU Gems 2*.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Using GPU for numerical linear algebra began at least in 2001.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It had been used for Gauss-Seidel solver, conjugate gradients, etc.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Computer video cards are produced by various vendors, such as Nvidia, AMD.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Cards from such vendors differ on implementing data-format support, such as integer and floating-point formats (32-bit and 64-bit).
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced a *Shader Model* standard, to help rank the various features of graphic cards into a simple Shader Model version number (1.0, 2.0, 3.0, etc.).
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Pre-Direct3D 9 video cards only supported paletted or integer color types.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Sometimes another alpha value is added, to be used for transparency.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For early fixed-function or limited programmability graphics (i.e., up to and including Direct3D 8.1-compliant GPUs) this was sufficient because this is also the representation used in displays.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This representation does have certain limitations.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Given sufficient graphics processing power even graphics programmers would like to use better formats, such as floating point data formats, to obtain effects such as high-dynamic-range imaging.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many GPGPU applications require floating point accuracy, which came with video cards conforming to the Direct3D 9 specification.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Direct3D 9 Shader Model 2.x suggested the support of two precision types: full and partial precision.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Full precision support could either be FP32 or FP24 (floating point 32- or 24-bit per component) or greater, while partial precision was FP16.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ATI's Radeon R300 series of GPUs supported FP24 precision only in the programmable fragment pipeline (although FP32 was supported in the vertex processors) while Nvidia's NV30 series supported both FP16 and FP32; other vendors such as S3 Graphics and XGI supported a mixture of formats up to FP24.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The implementations of floating point on Nvidia GPUs are mostly IEEE compliant; however, this is not true across all vendors.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This has implications for correctness which are considered important to some scientific applications.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While 64-bit floating point values (double precision float) are commonly available on CPUs, these are not universally supported on GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some GPU architectures sacrifice IEEE compliance, while others lack double-precision.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Efforts have occurred to emulate double-precision floating point values on GPUs; however, the speed tradeoff negates any benefit to offloading the computing onto the GPU in the first place.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Most operations on the GPU operate in a vectorized fashion: one operation can be performed on up to four values at once.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, if one color ⟨R1, G1, B1⟩ is to be modulated by another color ⟨R2, G2, B2⟩, the GPU can produce the resulting color ⟨R1*R2, G1*G2, B1*B2⟩ in one operation.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This functionality is useful in graphics because almost every basic data type is a vector (either 2-, 3-, or 4-dimensional).
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Examples include vertices, colors, normal vectors, and texture coordinates.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs are originally designed specifically for graphics and thus are very restrictive in operations and programming.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to their design, GPUs are only effective for problems that can be solved using stream processing and the hardware can only be used in certain ways.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the early GPGPU age, GPUs can only process independent vertices and fragments, but can process many of them in parallel.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is especially effective when the programmer wants to process many vertices or fragments in the same way.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In this sense, GPUs are stream processors – processors that can operate in parallel by running one kernel on many records in a stream at once.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programmers would use graphics APIs (OpenGL or Direct3D) to perform general-purpose computation.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] With the introduction of the CUDA (Nvidia, 2007) and OpenCL (vendor-independent, 2008) general-purpose computing APIs, in new GPGPU codes it is no longer necessary to map the computation to graphics primitives.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The stream processing nature of GPUs remains valid regardless of the APIs used.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A *stream* is simply a set of records that require similar computation.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] *Kernels* are the functions that are applied to each element in the stream.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the GPUs, *vertices* and *fragments* are the elements in streams and vertex and fragment shaders are the kernels to be run on them.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For each element we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Arithmetic intensity is defined as the number of operations performed per word of memory transferred.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is important for GPGPU applications to have high arithmetic intensity else the memory access latency will limit computational speedup.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Ideal GPGPU applications have large data sets, high parallelism, and minimal dependency between data elements.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In fact, a program can substitute a write only texture for output instead of the framebuffer.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is done either through render-to-texture (RTT), render-to-backbuffer-copy-to-texture (RTBCTT), or the more recent stream-out.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common form for a stream to take in GPGPU is a 2D grid because this fits naturally with the rendering model built into GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many computations naturally map into grids: matrix algebra, image processing, physically based simulation, and so on.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Since textures are used as memory, texture lookups are then used as memory reads.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Certain operations can be done automatically by the GPU because of this.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Compute kernels can be thought of as the body of loops.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On the GPU, the programmer only specifies the body of the loop as the kernel and what data to loop over by invoking geometry processing.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For accurate technical information on this topic see Predication_(computer_architecture)#SIMD,_SIMT_and_vector_predication and ILLIAC IV "branching" (the term "predicate mask" did not exist in 1967).
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In sequential code it is possible to control the flow of the program using if-then-else statements and various forms of loops.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such flow control structures have only recently been added to GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Conditional writes could be performed using a properly crafted series of arithmetic/bit operations, but looping and conditional branching were not possible.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Recent GPUs allow branching, but usually with a performance penalty.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Branching should generally be avoided in inner loops, whether in CPU or GPU code, and various methods, such as static branch resolution, pre-computation, predication, loop splitting, and Z-cull can be used to achieve branching when hardware support does not exist.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation simply applies the given function (the kernel) to every element in the stream.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example is multiplying each value in the stream by a constant (increasing the brightness of an image).
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation is simple to implement on the GPU.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The programmer generates a fragment for each pixel on screen and applies a fragment program to each one.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result stream of the same size is stored in the output buffer.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some computations require calculating a smaller stream (possibly a stream of only one element) from a larger stream.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is called a reduction of the stream.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Generally, a reduction can be performed in multiple steps.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The results from the prior step are used as the input for the current step and the range over which the operation is applied is reduced until only one stream element remains.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Stream filtering is essentially a non-uniform reduction.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Filtering involves removing items from the stream based on some criteria.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation, also termed *parallel prefix sum*, takes in a vector (stream) of data elements and an (arbitrary) associative binary function '+' with an identity element 'i'.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] If the input is [a0, a1, a2, a3, ...], an *exclusive scan* produces the output [i, a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, ...], while an *inclusive scan* produces the output [a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, a0 + a1 + a2 + a3, ...] and does not require an identity to exist.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While at first glance the operation may seem inherently serial, efficient parallel scan algorithms are possible and have been implemented on graphics processing units.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation has uses in e.g., quicksort and sparse matrix-vector multiplication.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scatter operation is most naturally defined on the vertex processor.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The vertex processor is able to adjust the position of the vertex, which allows the programmer to control where information is deposited on the grid.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Other extensions are also possible, such as controlling how large an area the vertex affects.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The fragment processor cannot perform a direct scatter operation because the location of each fragment on the grid is fixed at the time of the fragment's creation and cannot be altered by the programmer.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, a logical scatter operation may sometimes be recast or implemented with another gather step.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A scatter implementation would first emit both an output value and an output address.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An immediately following gather operation uses address comparisons to see whether the output value maps to the current output slot.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, scatter can be performed by indexed writes.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] After scatter reorders elements according to a map, gather can restore the order of the elements according to the map scatter used.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, gather may be performed by indexed reads.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In other shaders, it is performed with texture-lookups.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The sort operation transforms an unordered set of elements into an ordered set of elements.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common implementation on GPUs is using radix sort for integer and floating point data and coarse-grained merge sort and fine-grained sorting networks for general comparable data.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The search operation allows the programmer to find a given element within the stream, or possibly find neighbors of a specified element.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mostly the search method used is binary search on sorted elements.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia recommended GPUs for this application.
[src:metal-compute/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Check with developer or ISV to obtain certification information.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] GPUs are also increasingly being used for artificial intelligence (AI) processing due to linear algebra acceleration, which is also used extensively in graphics processing.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] This contrasts with earlier graphics controllers known as video display controllers which had no internal calculation capabilities, or blitters, which performed only basic memory movement operations.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The modern GPU emerged during the 1990s, adding the ability to perform operations like drawing lines and text without CPU help, and later adding 3D functionality.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Graphics functions are generally independent and this lends these tasks to being implemented on separate calculation engines.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs include hundreds, or thousands, of calculation units.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] This made them useful for non-graphic calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems due to their parallel structure.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The ability of GPUs to rapidly perform vast numbers of calculations has led to their adoption in diverse fields including artificial intelligence (AI) where they excel at handling data-intensive and computationally demanding tasks.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Other non-graphical uses include the training of neural networks and cryptocurrency mining.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Many companies have produced GPUs under a number of brand names.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 2009, Intel, Nvidia, and AMD/ATI were the market share leaders, with 49.4%, 27.8%, and 20.6% market share respectively.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In addition, Matrox while originally producing custom solutions, now customizes GPUs from Intel and AMD for workstation usage.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Chinese companies such as Jingjia Micro have also produced GPUs for the domestic market although in terms of worldwide sales, they lag behind market leaders.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Several factors of GPU construction affect the performance of the card for real-time rendering, such as the size of the connector pathways in the semiconductor device fabrication, the clock signal frequency, and the number and size of various on-chip memory caches.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] GPU performance is typically measured in floating point operations per second (FLOPS); Modern GPUs typically deliver performance measured in teraflops (TFLOPS).
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] This is an estimated performance measure, and should not be treated as fact, as other factors can affect actual performance.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs also include dedicated hardware blocks for ray tracing, video encoding, and AI acceleration.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In personal computers, there are two main forms of GPUs: dedicated graphics (also called discrete graphics) and integrated graphics (also called shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architecture (UMA).
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Technologies such as Scalable Link Interface (SLI), NVLink, and CrossFire allow multiple GPUs to draw images simultaneously for a single screen, increasing the processing power available for graphics.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] These technologies, however, are increasingly uncommon; most games do not fully use multiple GPUs, as most users cannot afford them.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Because GPU computations are memory-intensive, integrated processing may compete with the CPU for relatively slow system RAM, as it has minimal or no dedicated video memory.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] IGPUs use system memory with bandwidth up to a current maximum of 128 gigabytes per second, whereas a discrete graphics card may have a bandwidth of more than 1000 gigabytes per second between its video random access memory (VRAM) and GPU core.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] This memory bus bandwidth can limit the performance of the IGPU, though multi-channel memory can mitigate this deficiency.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] On systems with "Unified Memory Architecture" (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, and modern consoles, the CPU cores and the GPU block share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It is common to use a general purpose graphics processing unit (GPGPU) as a modified form of stream processor or a vector processor, running compute kernels.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] This turns the massive computational power of a modern graphics accelerator's shader pipeline into general-purpose computing power.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In certain applications requiring massive vector operations, this can yield several orders of magnitude higher performance than a conventional CPU.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The two largest discrete GPU designers, AMD and Nvidia, are pursuing this approach with an array of applications.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia and AMD collaborated with Stanford University to create a GPU-based client for the Folding@home distributed computing project for protein folding calculations.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In certain circumstances, the GPU calculates forty times faster than the CPUs traditionally used by such applications.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] GPU-based high performance computers play a significant role in large-scale modelling.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Three of the ten most powerful supercomputers in the world take advantage of GPU acceleration.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Since 2005 there has been interest in using the performance offered by GPUs for evolutionary computation in general, and for accelerating the fitness evaluation in genetic programming in particular.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Most approaches compile linear or tree programs on the host PC and transfer the executable to the GPU to be run.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Typically a performance advantage is only obtained by running the single active program simultaneously on many example problems in parallel, using the GPU's single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) architecture.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Substantial acceleration can also be obtained by not compiling the programs, and instead transferring them to the GPU, to be interpreted there.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] A GPU can be attached to some external bus of a notebook.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] PCI Express is the only bus used for this purpose.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The port may be, for example, an ExpressCard or mPCIe port (PCIe ×1, up to 5 or 2.5 gigabits per second respectively), a Thunderbolt 1, 2, or 3 port (PCIe ×4, up to 10, 20, or 40 gigabits per second respectively), a USB4 port with Thunderbolt compatibility, or an OCuLink port.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Those ports are only available on certain notebook systems. eGPU enclosures include their own power supply (PSU), because powerful GPUs can consume hundreds of watts.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Dedicated 3D graphics hardware dates back to graphic terminals such as the Adage AGT-30 from 1967 with analog matrix processors.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 1969 Evans & Sutherland (E&S) introduced the Line Drawing System-1 (LDS-1), which was the first all-digital system to provide matrix multiplication.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1969, the low-cost graphics terminal IMLAC PDS-1 was introduced.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It later saw use as an early 3D gaming machine with the likes of Maze War.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1970s, the term "GPU" originally stood for graphics processor unit and described a programmable processing unit working independently from the CPU that was responsible for graphics manipulation and output.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In professional hardware, in 1972 PLATO IV system becomes operational at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Between around 1973 and 1978, several networked multiplayer wireframe 3D games are implemented and popularized by users of the system.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1972, the E&S Continuous Tone 1 (CT1) "Watkins box" system (consisting of an E&S LDS-2 and Shaded Picture System) is delivered to Case Western Reserve University.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It offered the first real-time Gouraud shading.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 1975, a joint effort between Evans & Sutherland Computer Corporation and the University of Utah's computer graphics department results in the first ever MOSFET video framebuffer, capable of color and smooth shading.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] E&S Continuous Tone 3 (CT3) system was delivered in 1977 to Lufthansa for pilot training using computer simulation.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first graphics system capable of real-time texture mapping.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Ikonas made graphics systems with 8- and 24-bit graphics and 3D acceleration in the late 70s.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade system boards have used specialized 2D graphics circuits since the 1970s.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In early video game hardware, RAM for frame buffers was expensive, so video chips composited data together as the display was being scanned out on the monitor.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] A specialized barrel shifter circuit helped the CPU animate the framebuffer graphics for various 1970s arcade video games from Midway and Taito, such as *Gun Fight* (1975), *Sea Wolf* (1976), and *Space Invaders* (1978).
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The Namco Galaxian arcade system in 1979 used specialized graphics hardware that supported RGB color, multi-colored sprites, and tilemap backgrounds.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The Galaxian hardware was widely used during the golden age of arcade video games, by game companies such as Namco, Centuri, Gremlin, Irem, Konami, Midway, Nichibutsu, Sega, and Taito.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The Atari 2600 in 1977 used a video shifter called the Television Interface Adaptor.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Atari 8-bit computers (1979) had ANTIC, a video processor which interpreted instructions describing a "display list"—the way the scan lines map to specific bitmapped or character modes and where the memory is stored (so there did not need to be a contiguous frame buffer).
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] 6502 machine code subroutines could be triggered on scan lines by setting a bit on a display list instruction.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] ANTIC also supported smooth vertical and horizontal scrolling independent of the CPU.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1980s significant advancements were made in professional 3D graphics hardware.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Perhaps most impactful was the 1981 development of the Geometry Engine, a VLSI vector processor ASIC designed by Jim Clark and Marc Hannah at Stanford University.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] This processor is the forerunner of modern tensor cores and other similar processors marketed for graphics and AI.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine went on to be used in Silicon Graphics workstations for many years.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Silicon Graphics's first product, shipped in November 1983, was the IRIS 1000, a terminal with hardware-accelerated 3D graphics based on the Geometry Engine.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine was capable of approximately 6 million operations per second.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The 1981 NEC μPD7220 was the first implementation of a personal computer graphics display processor as a single large-scale integration (LSI) integrated circuit chip.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] This enabled the design of low-cost, high-performance video graphics cards such as those from Number Nine Visual Technology.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It became the best-known GPU until the mid-1980s.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first fully integrated VLSI (very large-scale integration) metal–oxide–semiconductor (NMOS) graphics display processor for PCs, supported up to 1024×1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the PC graphics market.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The Williams Electronics arcade games *Robotron: 2084*, *Joust*, *Sinistar*, and *Bubbles*, all released in 1982, contain custom blitter chips for operating on 16-color bitmaps.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first major CMOS graphics processor for personal computers.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The ARTC could display up to 4K resolution when in monochrome mode.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 1985, the Amiga was released with a custom graphics chip called Agnus including a blitter for bitmap manipulation, line drawing, and area fill.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It also included a coprocessor with its own simple instruction set, that was capable of manipulating graphics hardware registers in sync with the video beam (e.g. for per-scanline palette switches, sprite multiplexing, and hardware windowing), or driving the blitter.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1985, IBM released the Professional Graphics Controller, designed by later to be Nvidia co-founder Curtis Priem, which was a rudimentary 3D card with 640 × 480 256-color graphics which used a dedicated CPU to draw graphics independently of the main system.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It was used as the basis of cards by a number of makers (including Matrox) and its analog RGB signaling led directly to the VGA video standard.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Priem later in the 80s worked on the influential Sun Microsystems GX (also known as cgsix) accelerated 2D graphics card.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 1986, Texas Instruments released the TMS34010, the first fully programmable graphics processor.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It could run general-purpose code but also had a graphics-oriented instruction set.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] During 1990–1992, this chip became the basis of the Texas Instruments Graphics Architecture ("TIGA") Windows accelerator cards.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Following in 1987, the IBM 8514 graphics system was released.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It was one of the first video cards for IBM PC compatibles that implemented fixed-function 2D primitives in electronic hardware.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Sharp's X68000, released in 1987, used a custom graphics chipset with a 65,536 color palette and hardware support for sprites, scrolling, and multiple playfields.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] It served as a development machine for Capcom's CP System arcade board.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu's FM Towns computer, released in 1989, had support for a 16,777,216 color palette.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] For context, IBM also introduced its Video Graphics Array (VGA) display system in 1987, with a maximum resolution of 640 × 480 pixels.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Unlike 8514/A, VGA had no hardware acceleration features.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In November 1988, NEC Home Electronics announced its creation of the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) to develop and promote a Super VGA (SVGA) computer display standard as a successor to VGA.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Super VGA enabled graphics display resolutions up to 800 × 600 pixels, a 56% increase.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 SGI sold IRIS workstation graphics with 10-12 Geometry Engines and introduced the IrisVision add-in board for IBM MicroChannel bus (RS/6000) based on the Geometry Engine as well.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 as well, the first dedicated polygonal 3D graphics boards in arcade machines were introduced with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The 1990s again saw considerable advancements in professional workstation 3D graphics hardware from Sun Microsystems, SGI, and others.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The introduction of OpenGL by SGI in 1992 paved the way for standard hardware-independent 3D programming interfaces.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the mid and late 90s, professional hardware was being slowly eclipsed by consumer products which offered similar or even better performance, especially in regards to texture mapping, at a lower cost and on platforms familiar to end users.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 1991, S3 Graphics introduced the *S3 86C911*, which its designers named after the Porsche 911 as an indication of the performance increase it promised.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The 86C911 spawned a variety of imitators: by 1995, all major PC graphics chip makers had added 2D acceleration support to their chips.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Fixed-function *Windows accelerators* surpassed expensive general-purpose graphics coprocessors in Windows performance, and such coprocessors faded from the PC market.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In the early- and mid-1990s, real-time 3D graphics became increasingly common in arcade, computer, and console games, which led to increasing public demand for hardware-accelerated 3D graphics.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Early examples of mass-market 3D graphics hardware can be found in arcade system boards such as the Sega Model 1, Namco System 22, and Sega Model 2, and the fifth-generation video game consoles such as the Saturn, PlayStation, and Nintendo 64.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade systems such as the Sega Model 2 and SGI Onyx-based Namco Magic Edge Hornet Simulator in 1993 were capable of hardware T&L (transform, clipping, and lighting) years before appearing in consumer graphics cards.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 1994, Sony used the term GPU (with the meaning graphics processing unit) in reference to the PlayStation console's Toshiba-designed Sony GPU.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Another early example is the Super FX chip, a RISC-based on-cartridge graphics chip used in some SNES games, notably *Doom* and *Star Fox*.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Some systems used DSPs to accelerate transformations.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu, which worked on the Sega Model 2 arcade system, began working on integrating T&L into a single LSI solution for use in home computers in 1995; the Fujitsu Pinolite, the first 3D geometry processor for personal computers, announced in 1997.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The first hardware T&L GPU on home video game consoles was the Nintendo 64's Reality Coprocessor, released in 1996.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 1997, Mitsubishi released the 3Dpro/2MP, a GPU capable of transformation and lighting, for workstations and Windows NT desktops; ATi used it for its FireGL 4000 graphics card, released in 1997.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The term "GPU" was coined by Sony in reference to the 32-bit Sony GPU (designed by Toshiba) in the PlayStation video game console, released in 1994.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Pixel shading is often used for bump mapping, which adds texture to make an object look shiny, dull, rough, or even round or extruded.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] With the introduction of the Nvidia GeForce 8 series and new generic stream processing units, GPUs became more generalized computing devices.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] GPGPUs were the precursors to what is now called a compute shader (e.g.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] CUDA, OpenCL, DirectCompute) and actually abused the hardware to a degree by treating the data passed to algorithms as texture maps and executing algorithms by drawing a triangle or quad with an appropriate pixel shader.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] This entails some overheads since units like the scan converter are involved where they are not needed (nor are triangle manipulations even a concern—except to invoke the pixel shader).
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's CUDA platform, first introduced in 2007, was the earliest widely adopted programming model for GPU computing.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group that allows for the development of code for both GPUs and CPUs with an emphasis on portability.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL solutions are supported by Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM, and according to a report in 2011 by Evans Data, OpenCL had become the second most popular HPC tool.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 2010, Nvidia partnered with Audi to power their cars' dashboards, using the Tegra GPU to provide increased functionality to cars' navigation and entertainment systems.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Advances in GPU technology in cars helped advance self-driving technology.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] AMD's Radeon HD 6000 series cards were released in 2010, and in 2011 AMD released its 6000M Series discrete GPUs for mobile devices.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The Kepler line of graphics cards by Nvidia were released in 2012 and were used in the Nvidia 600 and 700 series cards.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] A feature in this GPU microarchitecture included GPU boost, a technology that adjusts the clock-speed of a video card to increase or decrease according to its power draw.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Kepler also introduced NVENC video encoding acceleration technology.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The PS4 and Xbox One were released in 2013; they both used GPUs based on AMD's Radeon HD 7850 and 7790.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's Kepler line of GPUs was followed by the Maxwell line, manufactured on the same process.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's 28 nm chips were manufactured by TSMC in Taiwan using the 28 nm process.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Compared to the 40 nm technology from the past, this manufacturing process allowed a 20 percent boost in performance while drawing less power.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Virtual reality headsets have high system requirements; manufacturers recommended the GTX 970 and the R9 290X or better at the time of their release.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Cards based on the Pascal microarchitecture were released in 2016.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The GeForce 10 series of cards are of this generation of graphics cards.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] They are made using the 16 nm manufacturing process which improves upon previous microarchitectures.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 2018, Nvidia launched the RTX 20 series GPUs that added ray tracing cores to GPUs, allowing real time ray tracing to be performant on mass market hardware.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Polaris 11 and Polaris 10 GPUs from AMD are fabricated by a 14 nm process.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Their release resulted in a substantial increase in the performance per watt of AMD video cards.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] AMD also released the Vega GPU series for the high end market as a competitor to Nvidia's high end Pascal cards, also featuring HBM2 like the Titan V.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 2019, AMD released the successor to their Graphics Core Next (GCN) microarchitecture/instruction set.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Dubbed RDNA, the first product featuring it was the Radeon RX 5000 series of video cards.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The company announced that the successor to the RDNA microarchitecture would be incremental (a "refresh").
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] AMD unveiled the Radeon RX 6000 series, its RDNA 2 graphics cards with support for hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The product series, launched in late 2020, consisted of the RX 6800, RX 6800 XT, and RX 6900 XT.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The RX 6700 XT, which is based on Navi 22, was launched in early 2021.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X and Series S were released in 2020; they both use GPUs based on the RDNA 2 microarchitecture with incremental improvements and different GPU configurations in each system's implementation.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In the 2020s, GPUs have been increasingly used for calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems, such as training of neural networks on enormous datasets that are needed for artificial intelligence large language models.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Specialized processing cores on most modern GPUs that are dedicated to deep learning provide significant FLOPS performance increases, using 4×4 matrix multiplication and division.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Early implementations, such as Nvidia's Volta microarchitecture, released in 2017, saw results of up to 128 TFLOPS in some applications.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Since then, AI acceleration cores have been a widely adopted feature in consumer and workstation microarchitectures starting with Nvidia's Turing microarchitecture in 2018, named Tensor cores.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] AMD originally implemented their equivalent "Matrix" Cores for consumers in their RDNA 3 architecture - however RDNA 4's Matrix Cores were the first to introduce FP8 acceleration - which is required to run the full FSR Redstone feature set such as Machine Learning Upscaling and Frame Generation.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] However, community made hacks on both Linux and Windows have allowed RDNA 2, 3, and competitor GPUs to run a weaker version of FSR 4 known as FSR 4 INT8.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 Pro, launched in 2024, has customized Machine Learning cores - which focus solely on INT8 acceleration - based on RDNA 4's for PlayStation Spectral Super Resolution to enhance framerates and image quality.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Intel has implemented their equivalent "XMX" Cores in all of their Arc GPUs, starting with the Alchemist microarchitecture.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] This is used for XeSS (Xe Super Sampling), XeFG (Xe Frame Generation), and more.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] Ray tracing has also been incredibly prevalent in the 2020s with some games, such as DOOM: The Dark Ages, requiring a hardware ray tracing capable GPU to even start.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] While it does lead to worse performance and less overall accessibility, id software claimed this saved several man hours and shrinked the game by over 100 gigabytes due to the game being entirely built around ray tracing .
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] In 2013, 438.3 million GPUs were shipped globally and the forecast for 2014 was 414.2 million.
[src:metal-compute/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the third quarter of 2022, shipments of PC GPUs totaled around 75.5 million units, down 19% year-over-year.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal is an object-oriented API that can be invoked using the Swift, Objective-C or C++17 programming languages.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Full-blown GPU execution is controlled via the Metal Shading Language.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal aims to provide low-overhead access to the GPU.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Commands are encoded beforehand and then submitted to the GPU for asynchronous execution.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] The application controls when to wait for the execution to complete thus allowing application developers to increase throughput by encoding other commands while commands are executed on the GPU or save power by explicitly waiting for GPU execution to complete.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Additionally, command encoding is CPU independent thus applications can encode commands to each CPU thread independently.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Lastly, render states are pre-computed beforehand, allowing the GPU driver to know in advance how to configure and optimize the render pipeline before command execution.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal improves the capabilities of GPGPU programming by using compute shaders.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal uses a specific shading language based on C++14, implemented using Clang and LLVM.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal allows application developers to create Metal resources such as buffers and textures.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Resources can be allocated on the CPU, GPU, or both and provides facilities to update and synchronize allocated resources.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal can also enforce a resource's state during a command encoder's lifetime.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] On macOS, Metal can provide application developers the discretion to specify which GPU to execute.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Application developers can choose between the low-power integrated GPU of the CPU, the discrete GPU (on certain MacBooks and Macs) or an external GPU connected through Thunderbolt.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal Performance Shaders is a highly optimized library of graphics functions that can help application developers achieve great performance at the same time decrease work on maintaining GPU family specific functions.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal has been available since June 2, 2014 on iOS devices powered by Apple A7 or later, and since June 8, 2015 on Macs (2012 models or later) running OS X El Capitan.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] On June 5, 2017, at WWDC, Apple announced the second version of Metal, to be supported by macOS High Sierra, iOS 11 and tvOS 11.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal 2 is not a separate API from Metal and is supported by the same hardware.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal 2 enables more efficient profiling and debugging in Xcode, accelerated machine learning, lower CPU workload, support for virtual reality on macOS, and specificities of the Apple A11 GPU, in particular.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] At the 2020 WWDC, Apple announced the migration of the Mac to Apple silicon.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Macs using Apple silicon will feature Apple GPUs with a feature set combining what was previously available on macOS and iOS, and will be able to take advantage of features tailored to the tile based deferred rendering (TBDR) architecture of Apple GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] At the 2022 WWDC, Apple announced the third version of Metal (Metal 3), which would debut with the release of macOS Ventura, iOS 16 and iPadOS 16.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Metal 3 introduces the MetalFX upscaling framework, which renders complex scenes in less time per frame with high-performance upscaling and anti-aliasing, mesh shaders support.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Also announced possibility to use C/C++ for Metal API.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] At the 2023 WWDC, Apple announced a brand new toolkit called the Game Porting Toolkit to port Windows 10/11-based games.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] It includes an environment to test binaries, translation layers from HLSL to MSL, and Metal-cpp bindings.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] Jeremy Sandmel announced a new Game Mode for macOS Sonoma, and Hideo Kojima announced *Death Stranding* for the macOS App Store.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] At the 2024 WWDC, Apple announced Game Porting Toolkit 2, along with the release of new games such as *Control: Ultimate Edition*, *Frostpunk 2*, and *Assassin's Creed Shadows* for macOS.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] At the 2025 WWDC, Apple announced Metal 4, a new version of the API featuring a unified command encoder system, support for neural rendering, and new technologies such as MetalFX Frame Interpolation and a ray tracing denoiser.
[src:metal-compute/metal-api] According to Apple, more than 148,000 applications use Metal directly, and 1.7 million use it through high-level frameworks, as of June 2017. macOS games using Metal for rendering are listed below.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan is intended to offer higher performance and more efficient CPU and GPU usage compared to the older OpenGL and Direct3D 11 APIs, by providing a considerably lower-level API that more closely resembles how modern GPUs work.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan is comparable to Apple's Metal API and Microsoft's Direct3D 12.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] In addition to its lower CPU usage, Vulkan is designed to allow developers to better distribute work among multiple CPU cores.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan was first announced by the non-profit Khronos Group at GDC 2015.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] The Vulkan API was initially referred to as the "next generation OpenGL initiative", or "OpenGL next" by Khronos, but use of those names was discontinued when "Vulkan" was announced.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan is derived from and built upon components of AMD's Mantle API, which was donated by AMD to Khronos with the intent of giving Khronos a foundation on which to begin developing a low-level API that they could standardize across the industry.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan is intended to provide a variety of advantages over other APIs as well as over its predecessor, OpenGL.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan offers lower overhead, more direct control over the GPU, and lower CPU usage.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Its overall concept and feature set are similar to those of Mantle.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] They were later adopted by Microsoft with Direct3D 12 and by Apple with Metal.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan is available on multiple modern operating systems and architectures, and provides a single API for both desktop and mobile graphics devices, whereas previously these were split between OpenGL and OpenGL ES respectively.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Like OpenGL, and in contrast to Direct3D 12, the Vulkan API is not locked to a single OS or device form factor.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan runs natively on at least Android, Linux, BSD Unix, QNX, Haiku, Nintendo Switch, Raspberry Pi, Stadia, Fuchsia, Tizen, and Windows 7, 8, 10, and 11.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] MoltenVK provides freely licensed third-party support for macOS, iOS and tvOS by wrapping over Apple's Metal API.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan reduces load on CPUs through the use of batching and other low-level optimizations, thereby reducing CPU workloads and leaving the CPU free to do more computation or rendering than would otherwise be possible.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Direct3D 11 and OpenGL 4 were initially designed for use with single-core CPUs and only received augmentation to be executed on multi-cores.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Even when application developers use the augmentations, these APIs regularly do not scale well on multi-cores.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan offers improved scalability on multi-core CPUs due to the modernized threading architecture.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] OpenGL uses the high-level language GLSL for writing shaders, which forces each OpenGL driver to implement its own compiler for GLSL.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] This then executes at application runtime to translate the program's shaders into the GPU's machine code.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] In contrast, Vulkan drivers are supposed to ingest shaders already translated into an intermediate binary format called SPIR-V (Standard Portable Intermediate Representation), analogous to the binary format that HLSL shaders are compiled into in Direct3D.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] By allowing shader pre-compilation, application initialization speed is improved and a larger variety of shaders can be used per scene.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] A Vulkan driver only needs to perform GPU specific optimization and code generation, resulting in easier driver maintenance, and potentially smaller driver packages.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] The developers of applications now can also more easily obfuscate proprietary shader code, due to shaders not being stored directly as source code.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] However, tools are provided that can decompile SPIR-V to human-readable high-level code.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] AMD states that "Vulkan supports close-to-metal control, enabling faster performance and better image quality across Windows 7, Windows 8.1, Windows 10, and Linux.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan 1.0 was released in February 2016.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] At SIGGRAPH 2016, Khronos announced that Vulkan would be getting support for automatic multi-GPU features, similar to what is offered by Direct3D 12.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Multi-GPU support included in-API removes the need for SLI or Crossfire, which requires graphics cards to be of the same model.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] API multi-GPU instead allows the API to intelligently split the workload among two or more completely different GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] For example, integrated GPUs included on the CPU can be used in conjunction with a high-end dedicated GPU for a slight performance boost.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On March 7, 2018, Vulkan 1.1 was released by the Khronos Group.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] This first major update to the API standardized several extensions, such as multi-view, device groups, cross-process and cross-API sharing, advanced compute functionality, HLSL support, and YCbCr support.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] At the same time, it brought better compatibility with DirectX 12, explicit multi-GPU support, (optional extensions for supporting hardware, e.g. some Nvidia GPUs, on e.g.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Windows and Android) ray tracing support, and laid the groundwork for the next generation of GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Alongside Vulkan 1.1, SPIR-V was updated to version 1.3.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On January 15, 2020, Vulkan 1.2 was released by the Khronos Group.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] This second major update to the API integrates 23 additional commonly used proven Vulkan extensions into the base Vulkan standard.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] The additional features of Vulkan 1.2 improve its flexibility when it comes to implementing other graphics APIs on top of Vulkan, including "uniform buffer standard layout", "scalar block layout", and "separate stencil usage".
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On January 25, 2022, Vulkan 1.3 was released by the Khronos Group.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] This third major update to the API integrates 23 additional commonly used proven Vulkan extensions into the base Vulkan standard.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan 1.3 focuses on reducing fragmentation by making the new features not optional in order for a device to be considered Vulkan 1.3 capable.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] The new features in Vulkan 1.3 include dynamic rendering, additional dynamic state, improved synchronization API, and device profiles.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On December 3, 2024, Vulkan 1.4 was released by the Khronos Group.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] When releasing OpenCL 2.2, the Khronos Group announced that OpenCL would converge where possible with Vulkan to enable OpenCL software deployment flexibility over both APIs.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] This has been now demonstrated by Adobe's Premiere Rush using the clspv open source compiler to compile significant amounts of OpenCL C kernel code to run on a Vulkan runtime for deployment on Android.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] The Khronos Group began a project to create a next generation graphics API in July 2014 with a kickoff meeting at Valve.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] At SIGGRAPH 2014, the project was publicly announced with a call for participants.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] According to the US Patent and Trademark Office, the trademark for Vulkan was filed on February 19, 2015.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan was formally named and announced at Game Developers Conference 2015, although speculation and rumors centered around a new API existed beforehand and referred to it as "**glNext**".
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] In early 2015, LunarG (funded by Valve) developed and showcased a Linux driver for Intel which enabled Vulkan compatibility on the HD 4000 series integrated graphics, despite the open-source Mesa drivers not being fully compatible with OpenGL 4.0 until later that year.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] There is still the possibility of Sandy Bridge support, since it supports compute through Direct3D11.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On August 10, 2015, Google announced that future versions of Android would support Vulkan.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Android 7.x "Nougat" launched support for Vulkan on August 22, 2016.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On December 18, 2015, the Khronos Group announced that the 1.0 version of the Vulkan specification was nearly complete and would be released when conforming drivers were available.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] The full Vulkan specification and the open-source Vulkan SDK were released on February 16, 2016.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On February 26, 2018, Khronos Group announced that the Vulkan API became available to all on macOS and iOS through the MoltenVK library, which enables Vulkan to run on top of Metal.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Other new developments were shown at SIGGRAPH 2018.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Previously MoltenVK was a proprietary and commercially licensed solution, but Valve made an arrangement with developer Brenwill Workshop Ltd to open-source MoltenVK under the Apache 2.0 license and as a result the library is now available on GitHub.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Valve also announced that *Dota 2* can as of February 26, 2018 run on macOS using the Vulkan API, which is based on MoltenVK.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On February 25, 2019, the Vulkan Safety Critical (SC) Working Group was announced to bring Vulkan GPU acceleration to safety critical industries.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Google's Stadia streaming cloud gaming service used Vulkan on Linux based servers with AMD GPUs.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On January 15, 2020, Vulkan 1.2 was released.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Alongside the Vulkan 1.2 release, the Khronos Group posted a blog post which considered that HLSL support in Vulkan had reached "production ready" status, given the improvements in Microsoft's DXC compiler and Khronos's glslang compiler, and new features in Vulkan 1.2 which enhance HLSL support.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On February 3, 2020, the Raspberry Pi Foundation announced that it was working on an open source Vulkan driver for their Raspberry Pi, a popular single board computer.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On June 20, 2020, a graphics engineer revealed that he had created one after two years of work that was capable of running VkQuake3 at over 100FPS on the small computer.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On March 17, 2020, Khronos Group released the Ray Tracing extensions, based on Nvidia's proprietary extension, with some major extensions and many minor changes, which in turn was based on Nvidia's OptiX API.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On November 23, 2020, these Ray Tracing extensions were finalized.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On November 24, 2020, Raspberry Pi Foundation announced that their driver for the Raspberry Pi 4 is Vulkan 1.0 conformant.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On January 25, 2022, Vulkan 1.3 was released.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On March 1, 2022, Vulkan SC 1.0 was released, bringing Vulkan graphics and compute for the safety-critical industry while being based on the Vulkan 1.2 standard.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On August 1, 2022, Raspberry Pi Foundation announced that their driver for the Raspberry Pi 4 is Vulkan 1.2 conformant.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On September 1, 2022, Mesh Shading for Vulkan was released.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] A new Vulkan Roadmap was announced on January 25, 2024.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] A new extension for decoding AV1 video was released on February 1, 2024.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Initial specifications stated that Vulkan drivers can be implemented on any hardware that supports OpenGL ES 3.1 or OpenGL 4.x and up.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] As Vulkan support requires new graphics drivers, this does not necessarily imply that every existing device that supports OpenGL ES 3.1 or OpenGL 4.x will have Vulkan drivers available.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] As of March 2023, Intel has split Vulkan driver support on Windows and on Linux.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On Windows, Skylake to Ice Lake supports up to Vulkan 1.3, with limited support after July 2022 as future updates will only cover security fixes.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Iris Xe and newer are fully supported as of March 2023.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On Linux, as of March 2023 there is incomplete Vulkan support for Haswell with it not being Vulkan 1.0 compliant.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Apart from Haswell, Ivy Bridge and Broadwell are also supported by a legacy Vulkan driver in Mesa called HASVK.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Skylake and newer being supported by a driver in Mesa called ANV.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On Windows, Vulkan 1.2 is supported from GCN 1.0 to GCN 3.0, with no further updates planned after June 2021.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On Linux there are various different Vulkan drivers with varying and overlapping hardware support.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] There is the open-source Vulkan driver called AMDVLK, developed by AMD which mirrors Windows support.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] There is also the proprietary driver called AMDGPU-PRO which is not recommended to be used for most users as of March 2023.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] There is also the recommended driver called RADV in Mesa developed by Valve, Red Hat, Google and others.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] This driver as of March 2023 supports all GCN and RDNA cards.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On Windows and Linux there is the NVIDIA developed Vulkan driver which supports Vulkan 1.2 on Kepler cards with no further updates planned after September 2021.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Maxwell and newer cards support Vulkan 1.4.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] NVK, an experimental, open source Vulkan driver for Linux based on nouveau, was announced in October 2022.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] It was merged into mainline Mesa in August 2023.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] The driver is currently Vulkan 1.4 conformant on Turing and newer cards, Vulkan 1.3 conformant on Maxwell, Pascal and Volta cards and Vulkan 1.2 conformant on Kepler cards.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Most modern Android devices support Vulkan.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Android 7.0 Nougat includes optional Vulkan 1.0 support, Android 9.0 Pie includes optional Vulkan 1.1 support, and Android 10 expects (but does not require) that all non-low memory 64-bit devices support Vulkan 1.1.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Android 13 expects under the same conditions support of Vulkan 1.3.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] On Linux and some ChromeOS devices, the open-source Mesa driver provides support for Arm Mali (Midgard and Bifrost), Qualcomm Adreno, and Broadcom VideoCore VI hardware.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] As of June 2022, Apple devices do not provide native support for the Vulkan API.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan support is available via the open-source library MoltenVK, which provides a Vulkan implementation on top of the Metal graphics API provided on iOS and macOS devices, though it has some limitations in regards to certain advanced API features.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] In June 2022, version 1.3.217 of Vulkan added support for Metal objects, facilitating import and export between the two APIs.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] In December 2022, Vulkan version 1.3.236 added small fixes for the interaction with Apple Metal.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] As of August 2023, Huawei provides supports for native Vulkan NAPI with the industry standard SPIR-V shader since HarmonyOS 4.0 API 10 and extended into HarmonyOS NEXT iterative system for current HarmonyOS versions.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Microsoft supports Vulkan 1.2 (and higher) on Windows 10 and 11, with a downloadable compatibility pack.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Vulkan is not backwards compatible with OpenGL, although there are certain projects that implement OpenGL on top of Vulkan, such as Google's ANGLE and Mesa's Zink.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Nor is Vulkan compatible with other graphics APIs such as Direct3D, Metal, and Mantle.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] Platform-specific graphics APIs implemented atop of Vulkan may also be able to run on alternative platforms.
[src:metal-compute/vulkan] For example, DXVK provides an alternative shared library intended to be used on Linux natively (without the Wine compatibility layer) to help with game porting.
